<h3>Literature</h3>
<ul>
<li> Textbooks on algebraic number theory
<br>
<p> A. Fr&ouml;hlich, M. J. Taylor, <em>Algebraic number theory</em>, Cambridge University Press, 1991
<p> K. Ireland, M. Rosen, <em>A classical introduction to modern number theory</em>, Springer, 1990
<p> J. Neukirch, <em>Algebraische Zahlentheorie</em>, Springer, 1992
<p> P. Samuel, <em>Algebraic theory of numbers</em>, Houghton Mifflin Co., 1970
<p> H. P. F. Swinnerton-Dyer, <em>A brief guide to algebraic number theory</em>, Cambridge University Press, 2001
<p> R. B. Ash, <a href="https://faculty.math.illinois.edu/~r-ash/ANT.html">online notes on algebraic number theory</a>
<p> B. Conrad, <a href="http://virtualmath1.stanford.edu/~conrad/154Page/handouts.html">online notes on algebraic number theory</a>

<li> References for Galois theory and commutative algebra
<br>
<p> M. F. Atiyah, I. G. Macdonald, <em>Introduction to commutative algebra</em>. Addison-Wesley, 1969
<p> J. S. Milne, <em>Fields and Galois Theory</em>, <a href="https://www.jmilne.org/math/CourseNotes/ft.html">online</a>

<li> More advanced books
<br>
<p> J. W. S. Cassels, A. Fr&ouml;hlich, <em>Algebraic number theory</em>, Academic Press, 1986
<p> S. Lang, <em>Algebraic number theory</em>, Springer, 1994
<p> J. S. Milne, <a href="https://www.jmilne.org/math/CourseNotes/index.html">various course notes</a>
<p> J.-P. Serre, <em>Local fields</em>, Springer, 1979

</ul>
</p>

